	<div id="id25b9" class="post">
		<h2 class="title"><span class="image-wrapper"><img height="47" alt="Apple is making a Web toolkit for Ruby" width="630" class="title" src="../../../resources/net.databinder.components.RenderedLabel/a802a384"/><span class="title">Apple is making a Web toolkit for Ruby</span></span></h2>
		<div class="byline"><span>
			<span>By <span class="alias">n8han</span>, <span>on January 26, 2007</span></span>
			<span id="id25ba" class="tags">
					{&nbsp;<span><a href="../../../code/tag/ruby/#selected-tag"><span>ruby</span></a><span id="id25bb">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../code/tag/apple/#selected-tag"><span>apple</span></a><span id="id25bc">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../code/tag/java/#selected-tag"><span>java</span></a><span id="id25bd">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../code/tag/web/#selected-tag"><span>web</span></a></span>&nbsp;}
			</span>
		</span></div>
		<div><p>(I predict.) And I want to go on the record with it. Here&#8217;s my thinking, in roughly chronological order:</p>


	<ol>
	<li>Apple/NeXT makes WebObjects for Objective-C, then ports it to Java because that&#8217;s where they (correctly) see server-side programming headed.</li>
		<li>Apple/NeXT likewise builds an interface to Cocoa/AppKit from Java, and for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhapsody_%28operating_system%29">Rhapsody</a> writes System Preferences in Java to show how serious they are.</li>
		<li>Apple&#8217;s <span class="caps">JVM</span> for PowerPCs is slow, so System Preferences is slow and makes people think that Mac <span class="caps">OS X</span> will suck. It is rewritten in Objective-C and is much faster.</li>
		<li>(Mac <span class="caps">OS X 10</span>.0 is still pretty slow and sucky.)</li>
		<li>WebObjects obtains moderate success but, being expensive, is ignored by the vast majority of Java Web programmers (who are now clogging every highway in New Jersey).</li>
		<li><a href="http://tapestry.apache.org/">Tapestry</a> is inspired by WebObjects, and is free.</li>
		<li>Ruby on Rails happens. Ruby programmers love Macs and aren&#8217;t afraid to screencast them all over the place.</li>
		<li><a href="http://wicketframework.org/">Wicket</a> is inspired by Tapestry, is even more clever, and is also free.</li>
		<li>Apple begins to include the Ruby interpreter in <span class="caps">OS X</span>.</li>
		<li>Intel processors begin to ship on Macintosh computers and the <acronym title="">JVM</acronym> performs well on them finally, but at this point Mac users have made up their minds to hate Java forever.</li>
		<li>WebObjects is freed / <a href="/n8/articles/2006/08/31/all-about-webobjects">aborted</a> / whatever.</li>
		<li>Apple discontinues extension of the derelict Java to Cocoa bridge.</li>
		<li>Apple announces <a href="http://rubycocoa.sourceforge.net/doc/">RubyCocoa</a> inclusion in Leopard, a bridge from Ruby to Cocoa.</li>
		<li>I mean, come on.</li>
	</ol>


	<p>Knowing that people inside Apple appreciate Web component frameworks (they invented them) I have a hard time believing Apple is peachy with Rails&#8217; unenlightened ActionController. Yes, I know that it too <a href="http://weblog.rubyonrails.org/2006/8/7/ruby-on-rails-will-ship-with-os-x-10-5-leopard">will be packaged in Leopard</a>. Hell, everything&#8217;s in Leopard (even Java!), so perhaps I&#8217;m reading too much into RubyCocoa&#8217;s inclusion.</p>


	<p>But if we imagine that Apple decided to start a replacement for WebObjects about 16 months ago, what platform would they pick? Obviously not Java (even before <a href="/n8/articles/2007/01/21/marking-down-your-territory">Jobs&#8217;s iPhone comments</a>). And if it were to be Objective-C, they&#8217;d just double-back on the WebObjects line instead of abandoning it. No, it&#8217;s got to be a ground-up rewrite in Ruby, which they could predict at that point as the next hot spot for server-side programming.</p>


	<p>Or maybe they&#8217;re not writing any kind of Web framework at all? Right, because no one is using Gmail and they&#8217;re all using Mail.app. And because the Web is not the future and Apple has no need to stay on top of writing applications for it. They can just use Google&#8217;s Web toolkit, and they love Google&#8217;s dominance of the Internet so much they aren&#8217;t partnering with Yahoo Mail instead for the iPhone. And anyway Rails&#8217; bastardized &#8220;<acronym title="">MVC</acronym>,&#8221; inspired by Sun&#8217;s famous Model 2, is the cat&#8217;s pajamas. Sure. Maybe that&#8217;s it.</p>


	<p>Internet Archive, hit me up, â€™cause I want proof of this in a year. Or three.</p></div>
